social_posts.post_text: Spring donabe plus the wagyu & caviar @boxer_akl just one of the many new dishes and services the team has pulled off in 2022 that makes me lucky to know such talented, determined people. There’s an energy that comes from creating with the right people for you that is the the most beautiful gelling, easy-yet-difficult, deeply fulfilling stuff out there; a spiritual high. Creation energy is my favorite drug and it never feels as good or soul-satisfying as with you @edverner. What a beautiful gift it is to be able to take something and alchemize it alongside the person you love. Here’s to more in 2023.

Where to Eat in 2023! Thrilled to be a part of this @eater package again and get to feature Tāmaki Makaurau Aotearoa, my new home. What a diverse and special place at the end of the world to get to live and eat in 🙏. A joy to work alongside @leishajones_ and @nicholasmancallbitel .The wahine @maimoa.creative overseeing Te reo of our most delicious endemic ingredients. If you’re keen to visit, head to highlights for a link to the Eater essential 38. While this list could only feature 38 of the endless special places and talents in our city if you ever need a specific rec or eager to hear about more, hit me up!

Counter dining is the best dining, regardless of price point. Sandwich counter, sushi counter, chef’s counter, deli counter, your kitchen counter with all your friends and scattered wine bottles and the food you’ve cooked all afternoon with the house smelling of garlic and San Marzano. 

I love duality of feeling dining autonomy yet wholly within the heart of something that a counter provides. It’s the perfect place for a solo diner to lock into the food experience. Sushi counters are my favourite. They can almost feel like an altar more than anything, especially when you’re in a pine lined temple to line-caught fish shipped half way across the world, served in a procession of jeweled bites.

This counter is one of my faves @shunjijapanesecuisine though I’ll still always hold a soft spot for the old location and how unassuming it was in an old BBQ drum shaped building (I think that’s what it was?). Here we have Miki plating some beautiful persimmon and chestnuts as a small winter welcome course. I recommend it as a counter you should pull up to.

Very honored to be included in this list of the most influential women in food & drink among some incredible friends, colleagues and those I’ve admired from a far. I remember an editor of mine, some time ago, discouraging us from pitching things that centered around women in the industry as a point of differentiation. Women as a hook to grab the reader. Such as: “This restaurant’s farm staff is 100% run by women!”Essentially, her (correct) thinking was there shouldn’t be separation from men and women in a novel way in our coverage as our language and inclusion as writers helps shape the conversation that women and men (and all other identities) are equal in these positions and we have responsibility in that reshaping. However, carving out extra space for what are still lesser known and highlighted stories in the form of an entire issue is only a good thing. More space to be taken up by women in this industry is a good thing. More discussion to be had is a good thing and more attempts (however messy and imperfect) to move forward into a new shape is just what’s needed to actually move forward. Good on you team & @kellibrett for this issue entirely dedicated to the stories of women. For this issue, I was tasked with putting together a few words on the very looming and multifaceted subject of what holds women in hospitality back. It was an assignment I felt a lot of anxiety over. There was an added pressure to “do it properly” that surprised me, even though, I reminded myself, I live this story too. 

Instead of going macro, I focused in on the minute: the small straws that break the camel’s back for young women everyday in the industry. Less ivory tower more boots on the ground.

I hope you’ll pick it up, for this and many other thoughts and stories, February 13.

Have you had Chwee Kueh before? Not the most beautiful but the most deliciously simple breakfast/ light lunch in SG (scroll to see). Made of rice flour mixed with water steamed in metal cups and topped with fried preserved radish and shallot, it’s one you can’t stop eating, playing between the contrast of the savory topping and cake. The Preserved radish is known as chai poh in Hokkian. You will see it written as choi poh (in Cantonese), chye poh or cai poh. In English, it’s the large Chinese white daikon/radish. Whichever language, it’s best with a little smudge of fermented chili sauce  and enjoyed while hanging out with Kim.

Other images, my fave Chinatown Complex Market & Food Center in Singapore outtake just outside on Smith Street, and, of course, Kopi (Singaporean coffee) from a fave stall inside.

Chendol! Huge difference between the regions and the good stuff and the bad here (I suggest to stay away from the neon green artificial jellies and look for lighter green with natural flavor). This one from Old Amoy Chendol is my favorite. Shaved ice, sweet coconut milk, green rice jelly with fragrant pandan, red beans, gula melaka (palm sugar/flower syrup). Perfect textures to play between in the heat.

What’s my favorite new bar in Singapore? I’d probably have to say @livetwicesg Inspired by a James Bond adage and designed with mid-century Japanese flair (complete with a slew of authentic pieces) this intimate space transports you to a retro Japan that might have never quite actually existed in this iteration but I’m very glad exists now. Like walking into a palpable nostalgia for a time you’ve never intimately known. It entirely avoids that back-of-the-mind feeling of theme bar that even some of the best end up not being able to when you dial into such a specific period and style. Also, how great is that angled mirrored ceiling? 

Brought to us by the team behind @jiggerandponysg under head barman @david.kim.js Live Twice brings the finesse you’d expect from this crew. Pictured on slide 2, their Vesper with ki no bi ‘sei’gin, Kettle one vodka, and tempus fugit kina l’aero d’or. @indra_kantono and @guoyigan always know their way around a perfect Vesper.

The gamut runs classics with striking execution and refreshing twists. My favorite of the evening and what I highly rec is the whisky and water. A solera of soft water imported from Hokkaido, Mizuwari with Nikka Coffey Grain Whisky and Nikka Coffey Malt Whisky that sits in a beautiful stone crock at the far side of the bar until it is integrated in a way that is deserving of the word remarkable. Simple perfection, just like the rest of the place.

I very much recommend you add it to your Singapore list.

Interrupting travel content for overdue food snaps with people who have brought me such comfort and joy over the course of my time in New Zealand. I am so grateful to each of you for your time given in both deep and easy moments; such serious and playful evenings. You’ve made New Zealand feel like a home even on the coldest days and backwards summer christmases. Our time is our most precious thing and sharing yours together will never be lost on me.
1. Crayfish creations at Alpha with @radish._ who is such a bit of light and spunk and always there with her ear and heart. Image from a night with @delaneymes, radioqueen, eons and eons in the making ;)
2. Congee with bluff oysters made by @culinaryjourneysnz who (she doesn’t know this) made the first dish I was able to stomach without feeling ill for some weeks, while dealing with health things, and was the edible version of her radiant human warmth. She’s the sort of person who cares for you especially when she sees how hard it is to do for yourself at the time.
3. @nick.landsman and @emmaogilvie housewarming snacks. These two are the besties who bring out being the baddest (in the best way) together. Whose wins and struggles seem to always cosmically mirror mine so that we never feel like there isn’t someone who knows exactly what you’re going through. 
Thanks to this wild land at the bottom of the world for such special people and memories 💛

There are iconic hotels and then there are *iconic hotels* @raffleshotelsingapore is the latter, alongside such properties as the Plaza, Claridges, Ritz Paris. Following a recent renovation Raffles has equally incorporated the spirit of its history and the vision of its future as a modern luxury destination, retaining the property’s unique heart. They’ve pulled it off and then some. Balancing the property’s culinary history with the Tiffin Room’s elegant Indian cuisine or the Long Bar’s Singapore Sling (and daily onslaught of cocktail tourists) with newer experiences like the Michelin-starred Le Dame Pic or fire-focused Butcher’s Block, Raffles has managed to upgrade in a way that uses the best of their historic oppulence while keeping up with Singapore’s face paced and ever evolving dining scene. At this level of hospitality, it’s a property worth a trip all its own. My favorite pick (when budget allows) in Singapore.

Soursop shaved ice. In high humidity all I want to eat all day is shaved ice or really spicy food things. Am I alone? How good is ice when every inch of your skin is sweating & air is thick as funnel cake? This is taiwanese style shaved ice so the ice itself is flavored which I have to admit I am partial to, over Japanese. @dearclarissa can you weigh in on any other notable differences we should know? And when I’m not eating icy desserts it’s all about:
2: paper dosa the size of kim’s arm with perfect fermented spicy coconut and tomato with mustard seed. 
3: phenomenal mutton curry with egg and onion roti. (Hot tip from kim: order a lesser devoured roti—like egg and onion—in order to make sure you get a fresh one).
3: Appam set of sugarplum dreams.
Raise your hand if you’ve had any of these bad boys

A peek inside @joalimaldives one of the most beautiful and luxurious remote island experiences in the world. As one of the Maldives newest and most oppulent resorts, this unique propety is paving the way for a new era of luxury tourism in the Maldives. #visitmaldives #joalimaldives #gifted #presstrip

Peek inside @restaurantzen.sgp one of the most well executed, delicious, & special dining experiences I have had recently. From the table side finishing of nearly every dish to the dedication and mastery of such special premium ingredients, see why Zen should be on your SG fine dining bucket list. Fave dishes were definitely the caviar and suckling pig (which is kind of cheating) the perfect collection of mollusks, tart chawanmushi, and kinki with tear peas. Such an unforgettable meal. Thank you, team!

There might be a time when the only real comforts you have between the difficulty are small, ordinary & familiar. Hunks of gold that weigh so much more in your hand than they seem possibly able to, to the eye. 

These rich simplicities might be like mine. Soft boiled eggs in their shells & fruit sliced by mum’s hands. Begrudging kid hugs from your little curly-haired brother (who is still child enough to give gentle childish sincerity), bad jokes from doctors that bring in the light & your family growing from love…life pushing (congrats zach & nelly, katie & kevin!). There’s those two kind sentences from someone you barely know, in your DMs. A good slice of pizza, bagel or taco or really anything you can stomach (when you can stomach) that taste like your precious memories. I like knowing that the chew of something delicious is at least one thing tangibly good about the present.

I’m so thankful to my family & friends (I love you) & everyone else in between for giving me these ordinary human things that made each day more manageable during what has been a very difficult time with health & family. As many close to me already known, it’s been a long journey of pain & debilitation for the last long while with days where using my hands, arms or being able to comfortably breathe & walk aren’t taken for granted. 

I’m incredibly grateful to pacific heart institute & for doctors who are genuinely invested & make difficult time as navigable as possible. It’s days like today, with family near, I know, despite all, I am incredibly lucky.

This is a very long & Hillary way of saying it’s been difficult to respond to you sometimes or voice how much your calls/ notes have meant. I’ll blame the safe but isolating avoidance cocoon I’ve been living in. But know how much you’ve all meant along the way, even if I haven’t been able to previously say it. Every little note.

Pictures of the simple joys of late, just scroll.

Last & not least, let’s all keep having fun & being kind & good to one another. If you’re wondering if I’d like to hear from you, the answer is yes. We’re here for a good time (like, according to Plato) not a long time. More ⬇️

The very wild & happy plot of heirloom odds & ends at my family home. (well, one segment of it). At 33, I feel humbled being back in a place of childish familiarity when I have never needed family more. It’s come as a beautiful shock to experience such feelings & acts of nurturing & care in new ways from my parents & sisters & brother & friends. Especially mum. If you are lucky in life (as many are not) the family home is a restorative womb (like love) in the most difficult times of life. Magic ancestral life blood pooling together into tribe. As part of our human story is to leave the family home to fully become “ourselves” there is a new plane of the self created, again, when this place is needed, once more, in the same ways you did as a helpless kid, now grown. How amazing to be amongst such exploding summer life. Such seasons of being together. Green & ripe generations of perseverance.

Also, the good one making all the future son-in-law points, harvesting the elderflowers and making them into something for another time.
Woo woo.

I think I’ve been lucky in that loving you has never been a difficult choice to make, no matter the season of our life. 

I know it’s been incredibly hard to choose to give up everything you’ve grown from the ground up, no matter how good the reason. The concrete room that you forged with sweat and sacrifice into what became more than just a restaurant but so much of your life. It’s been incredibly hard to watch you say goodbye to a place you’ve poured your spirit into to to create such an unbelievably special thing that has brought so much joy, creativity, and art to New Zealand & beyond. Especially when I know that choice came out of love for me. I love you old blues. 

I’m so proud I got to see & know this chapter of your life &, even more, to be a part of it. I’m so glad I got to know the epic unbelievable greatness that was Pasture!! All the beautiful regulars and staff that made it a once in a lifetime restaurant and invaluable piece of NZ tapestry. I’m so grateful for that last minute booking so many years ago when I first met you. Thank God you squeezed me in.

I’ll always remember eating there for the first time and how it blew me away, not knowing how much you would change and complete my life. Our time apart was the hardest thing. We owe our love to that techno-filled, mānuka-smoke-smelling, inside joke pit, fine-dining-family home. Thank you, Pasture, for giving me the best thing in my life. Edward ‘old blues’ Verner @chefedverner 

There’s the idea that all beauty stems from loss & death, right?The impermanence & fleeting nature of something intrinsic to our very idea of its beauty. Just like an unforgettable evening at a restaurant. I like thinking of Pasture just like that. 

How beautiful it was, made even more wonderful in its impermanence. How beautiful the next thing will be. 

Thank you for choosing me when I know it couldn’t have been easy. Thank you for choosing me & our family & snappers & Frank (kussy) & all the other future bits & bobs we get to have in all our other chapters. You’re it for always, love creature.

Photo: one of my faves by the great @brianbowensmith
Rhymes with: summer at mum’s ✨

There’s no place like home. Pretty sure being in the place you were born and grown (especially after 4 years as it’s been for me) has a special healing power in it. Nature magic, restorative. 

Extra points if you know what’s on slide 2. Use to spend the early evening with these puppies, during summer as a kid, filling them with chicken backs and hoping for the best before tossing them over the side of the docks.

Oh, and those blackberries taste like warm sunshine and the smell of salt water
King of the SGV @longoseafood ft. @andywangnyla @thatcherbakerbriggs @alistairlevine @clayfu.wine
